🧠 Big Idea

catch + throw allow you to:

Exit from deeply nested blocks immediately without raising an exception.

It’s like saying:

“If this condition happens, jump out of here.”

✅ Basic Syntax
catch(:tag_name) do
  # some code
  throw :tag_name
end


catch defines a labeled block.

throw jumps to that label.

The symbol must match.

🔥 Simple Example
catch(:stop) do
  puts "Start"

  throw :stop

  puts "This will never run"
end

puts "After catch block"

Output:
Start
After catch block


No error.
No exception.
Just exited early.

🎯 Why Does This Exist?

Imagine deeply nested loops:

catch(:found) do
  [1, 2, 3].each do |i|
    [4, 5, 6].each do |j|
      if i * j == 10
        throw :found
      end
      puts "#{i} * #{j}"
    end
  end
end

puts "Done"


If condition matches, it jumps out of BOTH loops instantly.

Without throw, you'd need flags or complex logic.

🧩 Important: It’s NOT Exception Handling

This is NOT:

begin
  raise "error"
rescue
end


It doesn’t create an error.
It doesn’t use rescue.

It’s purely flow control.

📦 Returning a Value

You can pass a value:

result = catch(:done) do
  throw :done, "Hello World"
end

puts result


Output:

Hello World


So throw can return data to catch.

🚨 What If No Matching catch?
throw :stop


Ruby will raise:

UncaughtThrowError


Because every throw must have a matching catch.

🏗 Where Is It Used?

In modern apps (including Ruby on Rails):

Rarely used in application code

Mostly internal Ruby library usage

Sometimes in callbacks

You’ll almost never use it in normal Rails business logic.

🔥 Interview-Ready Explanation

If interviewer asks:

What is catch and throw in Ruby?

You say:

catch and throw are Ruby control-flow mechanisms used for non-local exits from blocks. throw jumps to a matching catch label. It is not used for error handling and does not create exceptions.

Clean.
Professional.
Correct.

🧠 Mental Comparison

Think:

break → exits one loop

return → exits method

throw → exits any matching catch block (even multiple levels deep)

